      <hedline>
        <hl1>A World of Wizards And 13-Year-Olds</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from 13-year-old Susanna Heinz says making Harry Potter movies would destroy very thing that makes book series a phenomenon: its appeal to the imagination of children</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''All Aboard the Potter Express'' (Arts pages, July 10), you say that J. K. Rowling is concerned about how her character Harry Potter will be portrayed in the movie that will be filmed in the fall.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''All Aboard the Potter Express'' (Arts pages, July 10), you say that J. K. Rowling is concerned about how her character Harry Potter will be portrayed in the movie that will be filmed in the fall.</p>
        <p>I am 13 years old and an avid fan of the Harry Potter series. I have just finished the latest volume. I wish that movies relating to the series would not be made. I think that doing so will destroy the very thing that makes the series the phenomenon that it is -- its appeal to the imagination of children.</p>
        <p>A movie will destroy each child's unique and individual vision of the world of Harry Potter. In this era, children do not always have the opportunity to read and imagine things from their own perspective. ''Harry Potter'' has been a welcome exception. I wish we ''Muggles'' could leave Harry Potter's world to the wizardry of imagination.</p>
        <p>SUSANNA HEINZ  Chappaqua, N.Y., July 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
